- 'confidence score' is a measure of how strongly a recommendation is suggested to a user;
- 'total watch time' is the sum of all watch times for a given title by a specific user.

- "Most watched titles" refers to titles that have been watched the most by users based on their engagement;
- "Most recent engagement, playback, and recommendation events" means the latest instances of these activities for each user;
- "Average confidence score" is the mean of the confidence scores given to the recommendations.

- "Captivated the most attention" refers to having the highest total watch time and average engagement score;
- "Warmth of user engagement" is quantified by the average engagement score;
- "Top 3 titles" means the titles with the highest ranks.

sql:
SELECT title_name, AVG(rating) AS average_rating
FROM content_titles
GROUP BY title_name;

external_knowledge:
- "stars" refer to titles;
- "shine brighter" refers to ratings higher than the average rating;
- "galaxy of content titles" refers to the `content_titles` table.

sql:
SELECT COUNT(title_id) 
FROM content_titles 
WHERE rating > (SELECT AVG(rating) FROM content_titles);

SELECT title_name, description, rating
FROM content_titles
WHERE rating > 7.0;

SELECT title_id, engagement_score
FROM weekly_rankings
ORDER BY engagement_score DESC;

external_knowledge:
- "soared to the heights of popularity" refers to titles that have been in the top 10 weekly rankings multiple times;
- "shining like stars" emphasizes the titles' frequent appearance in the top rankings;
- "captured the hearts of many viewers" refers to the total watch time, indicating high engagement from users.

- Engagement score is a metric based on user interactions with content titles;
- Watch time is the duration users spend watching a title;
- The query combines these metrics to provide a more comprehensive measure of user engagement.
